<TEXT>
sovietbloc forces likely would require so 
much preparation to attack western europe that us intelligence 
would detect the activity months in advance according to a report 
published wednesday 
a study prepared for defense secretary richard cheney said the 
intelligence community believes we would have some 33 to 44 days 
of warning time and possibly six months the washington post 
said in its wednesday editions 
the newspaper said it had obtained a copy of the report by 
unidentified officials the judgment on warning time was said to be 
shared by the joint chiefs of staff the cia and the defense 
intelligence agency 
nato war plans had been based on the assumption that the west 
would have just 10 to 14 days warning of an attack the newsaper 
said 
a short expected warning time led to decisions to invest large 
sums in airlift capability and forward storage of ammunition and 
supplies 
the study said that while it remained possible for the soviets 
to launch a quick attack that would allow the west less than two 
weeks warning such a move would be quite risky for the 
soviets 
the study also found that during the 1968 warsaw pact invasion 
of czechoslovakia moscow was so worried about possible 
intervention from the west that it put its battlefield nuclear 
rockets on 10minute alert even though moscow clearly wanted to 
avoid a general war in europe 
</TEXT>
