<TEXT>
the navy frigate named after vietnam war hero 
lt cmdr wilmer paul cook performed a solemn mission scattering 
its namesakes ashes at sea 22 years after the combat pilot died in 
battle 
the uss cook left port monday morning and paused off the coast 
for the 20minute service before resuming maneuvers said navy 
spokesman cmdr david dillon 
it was believed to be the first time a navy ship was involved in 
the sea burial of its namesake dillon said 
cook a highly decorated a4 skyhawk pilot was shot down three 
days before christmas 1967 while leading an air strike over north 
vietnam he was listed as missing for more than 20 years before his 
remains were returned to the united states last year and later 
identified 
its nice that he came home finally its nice that hes back 
in the united states thats all i care about really said his 
eldest son wilmer paul cook jr it eased my mind to know where 
he is exactly for years i didnt know whether he was alive or 
dead 
cook 31 and his younger brother john cook 26 and their 
uncle john m cook jr 65 of titusville nj attended a 
portside memorial service aboard the frigate on friday 
the family requested his remains be scattered at sea from the 
ship that bears his name 
i wanted him to be remembered by the ship and the people who 
make it go the elder son said 
its a rare occasion for a ship and its crew to be able to 
honor the man for whom the ship is named and to commend the 
remains to the deep the frigates cmdr richard kalb said at 
fridays memorial 
hospital corpsman 1st class james gorham who attended mondays 
service on behalf of the family before returning to san diego by 
helicopter said the ship was brought to a stop and the crew of 250 
mustered to pay their final respects 
navy chaplain james sharrett led a prayer and read from the 
bible as the ships executive officer lt cmdr steven bostwick 
scattered the ashes into the pacific 
a sevenmember honor guard fired three volleys into a clear sky 
to salute the dead pilot and taps was played to conclude the 
service 
the uss cook was commissioned in 1971 in new orleans it was 
named after cook who was 35 when he died because of his valor 
dillon said 
navy frigates like this are traditionally named after military 
heroes he said 
cook a native of annapolis md and a 1956 naval academy 
graduate became an aviator in 1957 his carrierbased squadron was 
sent to vietnam in 1965 
he flew more than 300 missions in his skyhawk named the city 
of annapolis during two tours to the tonkin gulf on the carriers 
constellation and coral sea 
among his commendations were three distiguished flying crosses 
and five air medals for aerial combat he was considered an expert 
in the skyhawk and had been urged to return stateside to train 
others but felt he was needed more on the frontline 
on the day he was shot down the navy said he had turned down 
shore duty to lead the fateful air strike 
ill always go where my country sends me and will always do 
whatever it asks cook once wrote in a letter to his parents 
perhaps what i am doing may keep my two sons from going to war 
