<TEXT>
nina rubinstein was just weeks away from her 
doctorate when the nazis occupied her university in 1933 
her thesis was on her desk at johann wolfgang goethe university 
in frankfurt her formal education was over she would flee to 
paris later to new york 
next week miss rubinstein 81 will present her thesis to 
professors at the west german university 
if all goes as planned shell get the degree 
better late than never said david kettler a professor at 
trent university in ontario and one of those who initiated the 
effort to have her work recognized 
miss rubinsteins supporters say recognition of her work is a 
victory for academic freedom in a land where nazis expelled jewish 
and leftist professors and students among those who remained 
kettler said the lack of civil courage was a disaster 
for miss rubinstein a retired united nations interpreter it 
means she has to reread the 247page manuscript that sat on a shelf 
in her manhattan apartment for 40 years 
i had forgotten most of it she said monday im still not 
finished 
shell participate in a colloquium on the thesis which 
ironically concerns political emigration after the french 
revolution 
the thesis almost didnt make it out of frankfurt after the 
nazis occupied the building 
we were standing there pretty helpless she recalled it 
occurred to me that there was one student who was a nazi i 
wouldnt have talked to him normally i asked him to get my 
thesis he got it and i disappeared 
she went to paris where she stayed until 1940 when hitlers 
armies approached again she fled this time leaving everything 
behind including the thesis 
a french neighbor kept miss rubinsteins belongings and after 
the war traced her to new york the manuscript sat on a shelf for 
decades becoming not very important in my life until her 
halfsister hanna papanek tried unsuccessfully to get it 
published in the 1970s 
claudia honegger a professor at goethe persuaded the 
university to recognize the work kettler said 
this is important because i think the university is making a 
public statement a practical statement that it recognizes a wrong 
was done kettler said not to a big shot but to an ordinary 
person and they are making good on it not out of pity but on the 
merits of the case 
the awarding of the degree coincides with the 75th anniversary 
celebration for the universitys social science institute where 
miss rubinstein was a 25yearold student in 1933 
the institutes dean lothar brock said the event has a 
special meaning to both nina rubinstein and the university it is a 
good occasion not just to talk about these people but to have them 
here 
kettler said that while german universities were not responsible 
for naziera atrocities they were responsible for the way they 
dealt as institutions with the people who were victimized by their 
complicity during the nazi period there were very very serious 
sins of omission 
ms papanek said many of the other people who were expelled 
or had to flee have died its a lucky thing that nina is alive and 
can accept this as recognition of work she did in her youth 
miss rubinsteins professor was the noted sociologist karl 
mannheim who accepted her thesis but was suspended from the 
university along with other jewish and leftwing faculty he fled 
germany 
my professor wrote me a letter saying since you completed 
your thesis theres no reason not to get in touch with another 
professor and pass your exam miss rubinstein said he was 
naive 
she was concerned about the interruption but i must say that 
with all the political events dominating you didnt have too much 
time to think about that 
as a child miss rubinstein and her mother moved from germany to 
denmark at the outbreak of world war i then from the soviet union 
to germany when the bolsheviks took over in 1918 her topic grew 
out of the experience of russian emigres and is relevant today 
she said 
in our time the problem of emigration is quite important 
said rubinstein who is fluent in english german russian and 
french 
its very much a current topic said her halfsister what 
nina looks at is the experience of being a stranger it really 
became a forecast of things to come when she worked on it she had 
no way of knowing that 
</TEXT>
