<TEXT>
a federal law aimed primarily at compensating 
injured dockworkers also applies to railroad employees who clean 
and repair dockside loading equipment the supreme court ruled 
today 
by a 90 vote the justices ruled that three injured railroad 
workers from virginia are limited to receiving benefits under the 
longshoremens and harbor workers compensation act 
the three had sought potentially greater compensation under a 
disability benefits law covering the railroad industry the federal 
employers liability act 
someone who repairs or maintains a piece of loading equipment 
is just as vital to and an integral part of the loading process 
as the operator of the equipment justice byron r white wrote 
for the court 
because such work is essential to the overall loading 
process he said the longshoremens act is the exclusive remedy 
for injuries suffered by people who perform such work 
nancy schwalb and william mcglone who did cleanup jobs for the 
chesapeake amp ohio railway co and robert goode jr a machinist 
for norfolk and western railway co all worked at coalloading 
terminals in the hampton roads va area 
ms schwalb suffered a serious head injury in 1983 when she fell 
from a catwalk while going to a nearby area to pick up spilled coal 
mcglones arm was nearly severed as he was picking up coal from 
beneath a moving conveyor belt that same year 
goode suffered a hand injury while repairing loading equipment 
in 1985 
the three sued their employers under the federal employers 
liability act the virginia supreme court allowed the suits after 
ruling that their jobs were not covered by the longshoremens act 
todays decision sparked by the two railroad companies 
appeals reversed the virginia supreme court ruling 
the appeals were supported by the association of american 
railroads its lawyers told the justices that 300000 people 
employed by association members could sue if injured for 
compensation if the virginia courts ruling were applied nationwide 
the determinative consideration is that the shiploading 
process could not continue unless the equipment that goode worked 
on was operating properly white said 
schwalb and mcglone also were performing duties essential to 
the overall loading process he said equipment cleaning that 
is necessary to keep machines operative is a form of maintenance 
the cases are camp0 railway vs schwalb 871979 and norfolk and 
western vs goode 88127 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

