<TEXT>
armed state officials had no right to set 
up a riverblock to stop and search people canoeing on the saco 
river maines supreme court ruled tuesday 
agents from the department of public safety and the department 
of inland fisheries and wildlife set up the riverblocks on three 
weekends in 1988 to try to stop rowdy and illegal conduct on the 
popular river in southern maine 
but the supreme court justices agreed unanimously with a lower 
court judge who said the searches violated both the federal and 
state constitutions 
the ruling came in a lawsuit filed by daniel and jarlene 
hatfield of rochester nh who were stopped at a riverblock on 
may 28 1988 and subjected to an extensive search in which the 
state agents even looked inside daniel hatfields shorts the 
couple had only three cans of beer and no illegal drugs the 
justices said 
hatfield said he supports law enforcement on the river as long 
as authorities stop only people who give them a reason 
there are things that should be stopped such as excessive 
drinking and scuffles he said 
the state acknowledged that the hatfield search was 
unconstitutional because of a lack of probable cause but said such 
incidents were nothing more than isolated incidents or 
departures from normal appropriate procedures 
but kennebec county superior court justice donald alexander 
refused to dismiss the hatfield search as an isolated incident and 
issued a declaratory judgment that the riverblocks were illegal 
the state appealed leading to tuesdays ruling 
hatfield said tuesday he supports law enforcement on the river 
as long as authorities stop only people who give them a reason 
what made me decide to go through with this when they 
searched my pants that was uncool hatfield said he pulled my 
pants open and looked down inside there wasnt much i could do 
there was no reason for them to search us 
fish and game commissioner william vail said he had not yet seen 
the ruling so he does not know how it will affect future law 
enforcement on the saco which he said has more canoeists than any 
other river in the region and presents a challenge to police 
because no highways run parallel 
we patrolled the river in 1989 without the riverblocks and i 
think we were quite successful vail said i think we certainly 
maintained a law enforcement presence on the river this year 
at each of the 1988 riverblock checkpoints six to 10 armed 
officers and one or two police dogs were stationed on the banks of 
the saco canoeists who were stopped were asked to show their 
fishing licenses and asked if they had any drugs or alcohol 
some officers informed canoeists that they would not be 
prosecuted if they voluntarily surrendered any contraband but 
would be placed under immediate arrest if they did not voluntarily 
surrender any illegal contraband and such contraband was discovered 
in the course of a subsequent search the justices noted 
it was also routine procedure for the officers to inquire 
whether they had any alcohol aboard their canoes and if so to 
identify the state in which they purchased such alcohol the canoes 
and containers in the canoes of any canoeist who admitted to having 
outofstate alcohol but who was uncertain of the amount was 
searched 
each riverblock detected between 20 and 50 violations most of 
them being importation of too much beer fishing without a license 
or possession of marijuana a civil violation the ruling said 
</TEXT>
