of poland hungary and east germany in reducing the influence of 
the communist party and in moving from an authoritarian society 
to a democratic one 
during 70 years of trying to teach others how to live and what 
systems to build now we have learned that there are things we need 
to learn not only in the realm of technology but also in the 
fields of government and human rights he said referring to seven 
decades of communist rule in russia 
our main aim in coming here is to study your experience to 
find new forms of government he said 
burlatsky first rose to prominence as a speech writer for soviet 
leader nikita s khrushchev who was toppled from power in 1964 
since then burlatsky has worked as a journalist and sociologist 
gaining a reputation as a liberal before mikhail s gorbachev rose 
to power in 1985 
he has written speeches for gorbachev and has been an a 
prominent advocate for democratic reforms in the soviet union 
in his testimony tuesday burlatsky said that the soviet 
parliament known as the supreme soviet was expected to enact by 
january a longawaited law codifying recent liberalization of 
emigration laws 
president bush has said that passage of that law would clear the 
way for him to grant the soviet union mostfavorednation trading 
status lowering tariffs on soviet imports into this country 
burlasky chairman of the subcommittee on humanitarian 
scientific and cultural cooperation of the international affairs 
committee of the supreme soviet said his panel had played a key 
role in drafting the new emigration law ensuring that every soviet 
citizen has the right to leave and return to the soviet union 
the law will be a giant step forward in forming an open 
society in our country he said 
burlatsky read a catalogue of human rights legislation drafted 
by parliament including a law on private property a law on 
freedom of the press a law on freedom of conscience and religion 
and a bill on public organizations 
