<TEXT>
the soviet parliament tuesday approved a plan that 
apparently gave control of the disputed territory of 
nagornokarabakh back to azerbaijan but it also ordered the 
republic to work closely with the armenian majority in the region 
armenian deputies walked out of the hall when the directive on 
the nagornokarabakh region appeared at a closed legislative 
meeting on the final day of the supreme soviets fall session 
the neighboring republics of azerbaijan and armenia have been 
waging a bloody dispute over the region which is located entirely 
within the borders of moslem azerbaijan but whose population of 
124000 mainly christian armenians outnumber azerbaijanis by a 41 
ratio 
a special kremlin commission was formed in january to get 
control of the region where more than 60 people have died in 
ethnic clashes since february 1988 
the directive that was passed by the legislature eliminated the 
commission which was headed by arkady volsky 
nobody wanted to talk about it no one understood it said 
zuri balayan an ethnic armenian from nagornokarabakh in a 
telephone interview he was one of the deputies who walked out of 
the hall 
nevertheless it passed by a wide margin balayan said more than 
350 deputies voted for it only four voted against it and 20 
abstained 
asked what the likely effect of the directive will be balayan 
said only well wait and see 
the dispute has been one of the sources of continuous tension 
between the two caucasus republics in the southern part of the 
soviet union and despite the presence of soldiers some reports 
have warned of a virtual state of civil war some officials have 
compared the unrest in the region to that in lebanon 
the directive distributed by the tass news agency ordered the 
azerbaijan government in the shortest period of time to approve 
legislative measures guaranteeing the heightening of the status of 
real autonomy working guarantees to the armenian population of the 
nagornokarabakh autonomous region observance of the law 
protection of life and safety of citizens constitutional decision 
of all the problems that arise 
it ordered officials in azerbaijan to work with reinstated local 
officials in nagornokarabakh to write a new law guaranteeing the 
region full development in all spheres of government economic 
and culture on the basis of selfmanagement selffinancing 
territorial selfaccounting and freedom of economic and cultural 
ties 
armenians have dominated much of the local government in 
nagornokarabakh which was suspended when direct rule by volsky 
was imposed jan 12 
it was uncertain how the kremlin expected the polarized 
leaderships and population of the area to solve the problem but it 
was clear that officials believed it useless to continue direct 
rule from moscow 
the volsky commission was abolished and replaced by another 
commission under the supervision of the legislature which the 
directive said would oversee the work soldiers of the soviet 
interior ministry will remain in nagornokarabakh and obey the new 
commission the directive said 
the directive did not say who would be in charge of the new 
commission or exactly what its powers would be 
the dispute over nagornokarabakh brought hundreds of thousands 
of people into the streets of cities in both armenia and azerbaijan 
in february 1988 in its first effort to control the tension and 
address armenia charges of intention azerbaijani neglect the 
kremlin approved a multimillionruble plan to improve cultural and 
economic conditions 
local officials were ordered in the supreme soviet directive to 
ensure that no one tries to move settlers into nagornokarabakh to 
change the demographic patterns a special commission was set up to 
deal with the thousands of refugees who have fled violence in the 
area 
