federal officials began examining a rule 
tuesday that allows humans to swim with captive dolphins in hopes 
of determining whether the benefits to some people are outweighed 
by harm to the mammals 
in the florida keys home of three of the nations four dolphin 
swim parks supporters say the programs give humans a better 
understanding of dolphins and that the animals are protected 
against overexposure to people 
but some environmental groups say contact with untrained people 
could be dangerous and that too little is known about the 
transmission of diseases and effects on the dolphins natural 
bahavior 
both views were heard tuesday in islamorada as about 100 people 
attended a public hearing by the national marine fisheries service 
which regulates the dolphin swim programs a series of hearings is 
planned to help update the policy 
i have on file thousands of letters from people expounding on 
the virtues of their experience with the dolphins said michael 
wood general curator of the theater of the sea in islamorado 
there is nothing to suggest any ill effects to the dolphins or 
humans 
nancy daves hicks eastern regional director of the animal 
protection institute said dolphins have become victims of their 
own popularity 
dolphins do not knock on the front door of these facilities 
and ask to be let in they are chased netted and captured 
she said 
according to a federal study 40000 people are expected to 
participate in swimwithdolphins programs this year the four 
facilities have 34 atlantic bottlenose dolphins and one california 
sea lion in captivity 
the dolphins do not seem harmed by the interaction with humans 
said jeanne burns a spokeswoman at the dolphin research center on 
grassy key 
some dolphins in tanks with other dolphins actually want to 
get into the tank with the humans she said there doesnt seem 
to be any problems 
the center whose fiveyear swim program is the nations oldest 
allows 16 people a day in the dolphin tanks for 15 minutes five 
days a week 
besides satisfying curious tourists the nonprofit center has 
conducted studies that indicate swimming with dolphins help the 
learning process of emotionally and mentally disabled children and 
may improve competitive swimmers performance 
its one of those wonderful things that pull on your heart 
