the biggest stumbling block to normalizing 
trade between the united states and the soviet union has been a 
15yearold amendment added to the 1974 trade act 
sponsored by the late sen henry jackson dwash and former 
rep charles a vanik dohio the legislation prohibits communist 
countries from receiving favorable tariff treatment from the united 
states unless they permit free emigration by their citizens 
the amendment has meant that the soviet union cannot qualify for 
mostfavorednation status or the low tariffs that govern us 
trade with 150 nations instead soviet goods are taxed at rates as 
much as 10 times higher than the duties paid by other countries 
president bush said last may that he would recommend that 
congress grant a waiver of the jacksonvanik requirements once the 
soviet parliament passed a liberalized emigration law and 
demonstrated good faith in implementing the law 
such a law is pending before the supreme soviet and bush is 
expected to act promptly upon final passage of the measure since 
the soviets in an effort to demonstrate good faith have already 
allowed more than 50000 jews to leave the country this year 
for one product alone the soviets estimate that the lower 
tariffs will reduce the cost of a case of vodka in the united 
states by 15 
