<TEXT>
the supreme court in a dispute stemming from 
the 1981 settlement of the iran hostage crisis ruled today that 
american companies recovering money from iran must pay a portion to 
the us government 
by a 90 vote the justices upheld a 1985 law requiring 
companies that win claims against iran before a special 
international tribunal to pay 15 percent of the first 5 million 
recovered and 1 percent of the excess to the us government 
justice byron r white writing for the court said the money 
paid to the federal treasury is a reasonable user fee intended 
to reimburse the government for its costs also he said united 
states participation in the international tribunal assures the 
companies they will collect money owed them by iran 
white rejected arguments by sperry corp that forcing companies 
to pay the fees is an unconstitutional confiscation of their 
property and that any costs to the government should be borne by 
the nation as a whole 
as we see it sperry has not identified any of its property 
that was taken without just compensation he said 
the bush administration said tens of millions of dollars were at 
stake including some 127 million already deducted by the us 
government from claims paid to companies 
the financial deal that freed the 52 american hostages from iran 
included the release by the us government of billions of dollars 
in frozen iranian assets also the settlement set up a process 
permitting those with claims against iran to take them to an 
international tribunal 
the supreme court in 1981 upheld the power of former president 
jimmy carter to approve the settlement and that was not at issue 
in todays ruling 
sperry corp which leased computer systems to iran before the 
1979 hostage crisis severed relations between the united states and 
that country was awarded 28 million by the tribunal set up to 
handle claims after the hostages were freed 
sperry was ordered to pay the us government 42000 for what 
the government said was us expenses in helping resolve the 
companys claim against iran 
a federal appeals court here ruled in 1988 that the fee is an 
unconstitutional seizure of private property by the government 
in overruling the appeals court white said this court has 
never held that the amount of a user fee must be precisely 
calibrated to the use that a party makes of government services 
nor does the government need to record invoices and billable hours 
to justify the costs of its services 
todays ruling is not related directly to recent developments 
suggesting easing of tensions between iran and the united states 
the bush administration announced three weeks ago that the 
united states is returning 567 million in frozen assets to iran a 
move prsident bush said he hopes will prompt tehran to push for 
freedom for american hostages in lebanon 
the 567 million was being held in a fund to back up claims by 
american banks against iran 
the case is us vs sperry corp 88952 
meanwhile in an unrelated case the court ruled by a 90 vote 
that a federal law aimed primarily at compensating injured 
dockworkers also applies to railroad employees who clean and repair 
dockside locading equipment 
it ruled that three injured railroad workers from virginia are 
limited to receiving benefits under the longshoremens and harbor 
workers compensation act they had sought potentially greater 
compensation under a disability law covering the railroad industry 
the federal employers liability act 
justice byron r white writing for the court said the workers 
were covered by the longshoremens act because their jobs were 
essential to the loading process 
