<TEXT>
the 104yearold miller amp rhoads department 
store chain once a pricey trendsetter for christmas shoppers sat 
tuesday like a rack of last seasons fashions as officials sought 
buyers for the failing operation 
the demise of miller amp rhoads which has 14 stores in virginia 
and north carolina followed a gloomy trend in the retail industry 
that has left giants like campeau corp struggling with debt after 
buying allied stores corp and federated department stores inc and 
lj hooker corp liquidating six of its seven b altman amp co 
branches 
ironically miller amp rhoads was once part of allied the 
investor group that owns miller amp rhoads bought it from campeau in 
1987 six months after campeau won a 34 billion takeover battle 
for allied and began selling stores to pare its debts 
miller amp rhoads president john e stokely said monday the 
company had filed a plan in us bankruptcy court contemplating the 
sale of all its assets rather than attempting to reorganize the 
business 
stokely confirmed reports that circulated for the past week that 
may department stores co the nations seventhlargest retailer 
was negotiating to purchase four miller amp rhoads stores for its 
hecht co chain based in washington dc 
a news conference scheduled tuesday by hecht officials at which 
the purchase was expected to be announced was canceled may 
spokesman james abrams said there were still details to be worked 
out but there has been no change in our intentions whatsoever 
may owns 14 department store chains including the upscale lord amp 
taylor the 22store hecht chain had 759 million in sales last 
year 
the fate of miller amp rhoads other stores remained in doubt 
tuesday although stokely said negotiations were under way with a 
potential buyer for two branches in roanoke and lynchburg he would 
not identify the buyer 
the planned sale of miller amp rhoads came as other big department 
store chains including federateds bloomingdales division were 
also on the block campeau said recently it would sell 
bloomingdales to raise badlyneeded cash 
two other big chains new yorkbased saks fifth avenue and 
chicagobased marshall field also are up for sale their owner 
britains bat industries plc is restructuring its businesses as it 
fights an unwanted takeover bid 
retail industry analysts said it may take some time for miller amp 
rhoads to sell its stores 
there are a lot of department store properties on the block 
now and people are being careful about what theyre paying said 
analyst william smith of smith barney harris upham amp co in new 
york 
miller amp rhoads filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy court protection 
last july listing debts of 873 million and assets of 1296 
million 
the company suffered from the same sluggish sales that afflicted 
many other retailers it began to have cash flow problems soon 
after the investor group led by philadelphia developer kevin f 
donohoe purchased the stores from campeau for 65 million 
miller amp rhoads has been a basket case for some time said 
pamela stubing an analyst with moodys investment service in new 
york the debt from the 1987 purchase probably was too much for 
them she said 
donohoe who controlled 83 percent of the company said sales 
for fiscal 1989 were 1425 million down 31 percent from 147 
million the previous year 
stokely said miller amp rhoads would operate through the christmas 
season including afterholiday returns and refunds our 
customers can be confident that we will continue to operate 
normally he said 
miller amp rhoads had planned to trim the chain to eight stores by 
next spring leaving four stores in the richmond area three in 
hampton roads and one in charlottesville 
but stokely said the companys current circumstances and 
financial condition led the board of directors to conclude that a 
reorganization as a profitable going concern is not feasible 
