precious metal futures prices were mixed in active trading 
tuesday on new yorks commodity exchange as bargain hunting 
developed a day after profittaking sent prices sharply lower 
on other markets energy futures were lower grain and soybeans 
prices rose and livestock and pork futures declined 
gold ranged from 50 cents higher to 60 cents lower with the 
contract for delivery in december down 60 cents at 41350 a troy 
ounce silver was 2 cents to 6 cents higher with december at 5695 
cents a troy ounce 
gold prices continued mondays slide in early trading but 
reversed direction as speculators began to bargain hunt prices 
also were helped as the dollar weakened during the day nearing its 
1989 low against the west german mark 
gold continues to be bought by speculators said analyst 
peter cardillo of josephthal amp co in new york basically there 
still is a sense of fear about the strength of the economy 
energy prices declined sharply on the new york mercantile 
exchange as traders reacted to news that opec ministers reached a 
new production agreement that would raise the groups output 
ceiling to 22 million barrels a day and maintain a target price of 
18 a barrel 
analyst robert baker of prudentialbache securities inc in new 
york said the agreement reached in vienna austria had a few 
more leaks in terms of quota dicipline than was desired by the 
market 
the agreement was signed with the recognition that the united 
arab emirates would continue to overproduce baker said adding 
that kuwait would also continue to surpass its quota 
the united arab emirates and kuwait have been producing 2 
million barrels a day apiece or double their current quotas 
west texas intermediate crude oil was 29 cents to 43 cents lower 
with january at 1925 cents a barrel heating oil was 61 cent to 
94 cent lower with december at 6031 cents a gallon unleaded 
gasoline was 80 cent to 136 cents higher with december at 4953 
cents a gallon 
grain and soybean futures prices closed higher on the chicago 
board of trade despite the lack of news to influence trading 
soybean futures rose as traders reacted to a sense that the 
market was oversold in the wake of mondays selloff of soybean 
futures on slack export sales and bearish technical signals 
there wasnt much selling in the market today it was all done 
monday said dale gustafson of drexel burnham lambert inc 
soybeans also received support from the malaysian palm oil 
market where futures were higher monday after last weeks 
weakness gustafson said 
palm oil accounts for the largest share of edible vegetable oil 
traded internationally its price has a big effect on soy oil 
prices gustafson said 
wheat prices gained in the wake of the national weather 
services six to 10day forecast released monday the outlook 
calls for continued dry weather in winter wheat crop areas 
corn prices were higher on expectations of another week of 
strong export shipments analysts said 
wheat was a cent lower to 1 cents higher with december at 
406 a bushel corn was cent to 2 cents higher with december 
at 234 a bushel oats were cent to 1 cents higher with 
december 143 a bushel soybeans were a cent to 3 cents higher 
with january at 579 cents a bushel 
livestock and pork futures were lower on the chicago mercantile 
exchange 
frozen pork belly prices fell the daily limit as profittaking 
took over after a run up of prices in recent sessions 
cattle prices were lower in anticipation of increased marketing 
by producers and analysts said beef demand has slackened because 
retailers shelves are full 
