<TEXT>
lone star industries inc which makes 
cement and other construction materials said it plans to sell 
several businesses real estate and other assets as part of a 
restructuring 
the board of directors adopted the program to improve the 
companys cash flow and profitability said james e stewart 
chairman and chief executive officer in a statement issued monday 
the company said the reorganization would result in a 250 
million aftertax charge in the fourth quarter but did not say how 
the charge would affect results for that period 
lone stars net income in the third quarter was down 66 percent 
from the same quarter last year to 18 million from 55 million 
lone star was not specific about which businesses it plans to 
sell but said several in the southwest were targeted it also said 
it would sell interests in certain joint ventures an investment in 
preferred stock and surplus real estate 
the company has 22 cement plants including operations in texas 
louisiana and oklahoma 
the cash generated from selling assets would be used to repay 
debts and improve the companys liquidity the company said 
the new lone star will be made up of the companys strongest 
and most profitable assets and will emerge as a strong and healthy 
industry leader capable of reestablishing a longterm record of 
profitability and rewards to its shareholders stewart said in 
his statement 
lone star has been hurt by continued softness in the 
construction industry it also is the target of lawsuits by 
railroad companies that claim lone star sold them defective 
railroad ties although a spokesman said the suits had no 
connection to the restructuring 
lone star is a major producer of cement readymixed concrete 
sand and gravel crushed stone and precast concrete products 
